WEBVTT

00:00.667 --> 00:02.667
             [♪♪♪]

00:04.505 --> 00:06.238
Is there any more coffee,
        Jeannie?

00:08.074 --> 00:09.974
         Oh, thank you.

00:09.976 --> 00:11.343
          Master.
                      Hm?

00:11.345 --> 00:12.744
Why do you not work
  at home today?

00:12.746 --> 00:15.246
  Is this not much nicer
than a stuffy, old office?

00:15.248 --> 00:16.948
                No, it's not
           a stuffy, old office.

00:16.950 --> 00:19.318
    Besides, Roger's gonna be
 picking me up in a few minutes.

00:19.320 --> 00:21.353
           We have a conference
          with General Peterson.

00:21.355 --> 00:22.387
         And I'm taking up a 104

00:22.389 --> 00:24.088
        with some experimental
           equipment on it.

00:24.090 --> 00:25.123
         Now, that's not stuffy.

00:25.125 --> 00:26.958
And you find that exciting?

00:26.960 --> 00:28.460
               It's not supposed
                to be exciting.

00:28.462 --> 00:29.961
Well, then why do you do it?

00:29.963 --> 00:31.763
               'Cause I like it.

00:31.765 --> 00:33.932
Good morning, Major Healey.

00:33.934 --> 00:35.734
                  Oh, hi, Roge.
                  Come on out.

00:38.572 --> 00:40.339
                     Roge?

00:40.341 --> 00:41.973
                  What's wrong?

00:41.975 --> 00:43.875
 Look, uh, we'd better
get over to the office.

00:43.877 --> 00:46.545
       We have a meeting in, uh,
         30 minutes, so, uh...

00:46.547 --> 00:49.414
      Well, you got time
     for a cup of coffee.

00:49.416 --> 00:50.649
                     Very nice.

00:50.651 --> 00:52.351
       Sit down. Tell me
      what's worrying you.

00:52.353 --> 00:54.820
   Oh, what could be worrying me
  when I have a friend like you?

00:54.822 --> 00:56.588
          Have you had any other
            nice wishes today?

00:56.590 --> 00:57.622
     What's on your mind?

00:57.624 --> 01:00.225
     There's nothing on my mind.

01:01.895 --> 01:04.663
I'll tell you what's on my mind.
  You know what's on my mind?

01:04.665 --> 01:06.565
 If I had my own private genie
       and my best friend

01:06.567 --> 01:09.067
      wanted to borrow her
     from me, I'd let him.

01:09.069 --> 01:10.802
                 Oh, not again.

01:10.804 --> 01:12.371
               Roger, we've been
               through all this.

01:12.373 --> 01:13.939
 Jeannie won't do me any harm.

01:13.941 --> 01:16.107
Oh, of course not.
           You see?

01:16.109 --> 01:18.410
   She won't mean to, but that's
     what will happen, anyway.

01:18.412 --> 01:19.411
            Well, you know that.

01:19.413 --> 01:20.913
   I don't want to keep her.

01:20.915 --> 01:22.414
            All I want
     is three little wishes.

01:22.416 --> 01:23.849
                        No.

01:23.851 --> 01:25.783
          Two wishes?
                      Roger.

01:25.785 --> 01:28.119
    One teensy-weensy wish?

01:28.121 --> 01:29.888
Oh, please, may I, master?

01:29.890 --> 01:31.356
                         Listen,

01:31.358 --> 01:33.425
I'll never ask you another thing
       in my whole life.

01:33.427 --> 01:35.126
         Just one wish.
   What have you got to lose?

01:35.128 --> 01:37.195
           I don't know.
   I haven't heard the wish yet.

01:38.899 --> 01:41.132
            All right, go ahead,
              give him a wish.

01:41.134 --> 01:42.233
    [GIGGLES]

01:42.235 --> 01:45.270
      All I want is one--

01:45.272 --> 01:47.573
        One--? One wish?

01:47.575 --> 01:49.074
 You're going to give me a wish?

01:49.076 --> 01:50.709
              Oh!

01:50.711 --> 01:51.977
 Only one now.
Don't go crazy.

01:51.979 --> 01:53.211
                   Go crazy?

01:53.213 --> 01:54.880
             I'm the richest man
             in the whole world.

01:54.882 --> 01:57.148
                 Oh, am I rich.
               Yachts, chateaus.

01:57.150 --> 01:58.583
Ah. You wish to be
 the richest man

01:58.585 --> 01:59.751
in the whole world.

01:59.753 --> 02:00.786
              No!

02:00.788 --> 02:02.187
       Oh, wait a minute.
         Wait a minute.

02:02.189 --> 02:03.855
      Maybe I should look
       like Gregory Peck.

02:03.857 --> 02:06.325
 Ah, can you imagine all those
 girls falling in love with me?

02:06.327 --> 02:08.627
    Ah...
Gregory Peck.

02:08.628 --> 02:09.661
             Wait!

02:09.663 --> 02:11.797
 Wait a minute, wait a minute.

02:11.799 --> 02:12.965
      With all that money,

02:12.967 --> 02:14.666
      I don't have to look
       like Gregory Peck.

02:14.668 --> 02:16.635
      With all that money,
   I should live long enough

02:16.637 --> 02:17.703
          to spend it.

02:17.705 --> 02:19.204
      Maybe I should wish
        for a long life.

02:19.206 --> 02:20.505
  Long life.

02:20.507 --> 02:22.040
           Oh, wait!

02:22.042 --> 02:24.443
      Roger, would you hurry up?
     We got a meeting, remember?

02:24.445 --> 02:25.944
      Hold your tongue, will ya?

02:25.946 --> 02:28.513
  You may be talking to the next
 president of the United States.

02:28.515 --> 02:29.614
           Can you imagine that?

02:29.616 --> 02:32.117
               The president
           of the United States.

02:32.119 --> 02:34.353
         Oh, I'm so sorry, Tony.

02:34.355 --> 02:35.754
                 Oh, I wished
             I hadn't done that.

02:38.359 --> 02:43.094
 Oh, Jeannie, you're wonderful.
And I wished I hadn't done that.

02:43.096 --> 02:46.631
      I wished I hadn't done it?

02:46.633 --> 02:48.032
                  Oh, no!

02:48.034 --> 02:50.034
             [♪♪♪]

02:52.272 --> 02:54.272
             [♪♪♪]

03:40.687 --> 03:42.687
             [♪♪♪]

03:46.926 --> 03:49.427
  You can't do this to the next
 president of the United States.

03:49.429 --> 03:50.462
              You said one wish.

03:50.464 --> 03:51.463
       And you've had it.

03:51.465 --> 03:52.797
        You mean, I've been had.

03:52.799 --> 03:55.266
Oh, I am sorry, Major Healey,
but you did wish for the stain

03:55.268 --> 03:56.267
to disappear.

03:56.269 --> 03:57.535
         That's right.
         Thanks, Roge.

03:57.537 --> 03:58.936
                 Oh, thanks,
            think nothing of it.

03:58.938 --> 04:01.172
       That's the only 5 billion
        dollar stain in history.

04:01.174 --> 04:02.240
       Goodbye, Jeannie.

04:02.242 --> 04:03.941
            Wait a minute!
      You mean that was my wish?

04:03.943 --> 04:05.043
         That's right.
                       Oh, wait.

04:05.045 --> 04:06.478
Stains don't count.

04:06.480 --> 04:09.314
[ARGUING]

04:09.316 --> 04:11.316
             [♪♪♪]

04:41.415 --> 04:43.415
      [INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

04:55.595 --> 04:57.529
            [HOSE BLOWING AIR]

05:01.701 --> 05:03.068
Boy, these flies are killing me.

05:03.070 --> 05:04.936
             Whew!

05:04.938 --> 05:06.304
            Get 'em.

05:06.306 --> 05:08.005
       Get 'em, get 'em.

05:08.007 --> 05:09.040
                 Hey, hey.

05:09.042 --> 05:10.041
Will ya? Will ya?

05:10.043 --> 05:11.042
        I'm-- I'm sorry.

05:11.044 --> 05:12.243
             Whew.

05:12.245 --> 05:13.378
       Listen, I wanna...

05:17.784 --> 05:19.617
              Oh. Sorry.

05:19.619 --> 05:21.252
Look at the grease
  on that thing.

05:22.889 --> 05:24.322
     All right,
what were you saying?

05:24.324 --> 05:26.491
Oh, I was just saying that, uh--
      I was just saying--

05:26.493 --> 05:27.559
               Oh, Major Nelson.

05:27.561 --> 05:28.593
                  Hey, look out!

05:28.595 --> 05:29.861
   Roger, what are you doing?

05:29.863 --> 05:30.862
        Oh, I'm so--

05:35.202 --> 05:37.502
             I don't understand.

05:37.504 --> 05:39.671
        I just saw you smear him
            with that grease,

05:39.673 --> 05:42.073
               and his uniform
            is absolutely clean.

05:42.075 --> 05:43.274
Yes. Yes, it is,
   isn't it?

05:43.276 --> 05:45.143
  Well, how do you explain that,
           Major Nelson?

05:45.145 --> 05:47.145
  Well, there's really
nothing to explain, sir.

05:47.147 --> 05:48.212
              I know what I saw.

05:48.214 --> 05:50.015
Yeah, Roger, will you
put that thing down?

05:50.017 --> 05:51.983
               Just put it down.

05:51.985 --> 05:53.417
   We gotta stop horsing around.

05:53.419 --> 05:55.720
                       [YELPS]

05:59.626 --> 06:01.592
Your blouse won't get dirty.

06:01.594 --> 06:03.928
 Yeah, it must be the experiment
      we're working on, sir.

06:03.930 --> 06:06.731
This is the most incredible
   thing I've ever seen.

06:06.733 --> 06:08.533
    And since you've
been here, Major Nelson,

06:08.535 --> 06:10.601
I've seen some pretty
 incredible things.

06:10.603 --> 06:12.303
             Yeah. Well, there's
             nothing to it, sir.

06:12.305 --> 06:13.905
     It's the simplest thing
          in the world.

06:13.907 --> 06:15.140
How do you do it?

06:15.142 --> 06:16.941
    It's the X Factor, sir.

06:16.943 --> 06:19.144
      You just, uh, spray
  this fluid on the material,

06:19.146 --> 06:20.545
        and it keeps it
        from permeating.

06:21.748 --> 06:23.347
          Remarkable.

06:23.349 --> 06:25.884
Yes. well, if you'll excuse us,
      we have a briefing.

06:25.886 --> 06:28.386
            Briefing.
       What do you mean?

06:28.388 --> 06:30.288
         Oh, briefing.

06:30.290 --> 06:31.589
                 ROGER:
               Briefing.

06:31.591 --> 06:33.291
          Let's don't be late
           for the briefing.

06:43.336 --> 06:46.271
              Oh, general,
        I've got to talk to you.

06:46.273 --> 06:47.438
Is anything wrong?

06:47.440 --> 06:48.439
                         Wrong?

06:48.441 --> 06:51.409
     Oh, uh, just a moment, sir.

06:51.411 --> 06:54.712
 Oh, captain, would you please
see the general isn't disturbed?

06:54.714 --> 06:57.182
                     Thank you.

06:57.184 --> 07:01.352
            General Peterson,
         unless I miss my guess,

07:01.354 --> 07:03.087
           we'll be showing this

07:03.089 --> 07:06.091
       to the president of
 the United States by nightfall.

07:06.093 --> 07:08.126
        Looks like a can
         of fly spray.

07:08.128 --> 07:11.462
    It might look like a can
       of fly spray, sir,

07:11.464 --> 07:14.966
   but it's probably the most
 exciting discovery ever made.

07:14.968 --> 07:16.367
  Would you mind standing up?

07:16.369 --> 07:17.602
    You want me to stand up?

07:17.604 --> 07:19.504
                Please, general.

07:21.875 --> 07:25.043
Well, uh, what does it do?

07:25.045 --> 07:27.478
            You'll see, general.
                 You'll see.

07:27.480 --> 07:29.480
        It has a X Factor in it.

07:29.482 --> 07:35.186
             Now, first we spray
               on the X Factor,

07:35.188 --> 07:39.123
               then we put on...

07:39.125 --> 07:41.392
              some black grease.

07:41.394 --> 07:43.227
               Just like this.

07:43.229 --> 07:45.496
                 Now, you watch.
                  Watch closely.

08:00.113 --> 08:01.546
                         Tea?

08:01.548 --> 08:03.548
                  Yeah.

08:03.550 --> 08:05.050
             No, no, no.

08:05.052 --> 08:07.285
   Oh, I wish I hadn't blown
    that wish this morning.

08:07.287 --> 08:08.920
             You oughta consider
               yourself lucky.

08:08.922 --> 08:11.323
   It's the first time I've ever
   known Jeannie to grant a wish

08:11.325 --> 08:12.723
                and not have it
               cause a disaster.

08:12.725 --> 08:14.059
       A disaster?
                           Yeah.

08:15.695 --> 08:17.795
                 Oh, a disaster.
                  Wait a minute.

08:17.797 --> 08:18.896
       You know how big this is?

08:18.898 --> 08:20.465
      A material
that's indestructible?

08:20.467 --> 08:21.799
                 Indestructible?
                    Who said?

08:21.801 --> 08:24.235
Listen, when Jeannie blinks,
  she doesn't fool around.

08:24.237 --> 08:26.404
       Of course not.

08:26.406 --> 08:29.074
   Say, you know you've stumbled
  on something really marvelous.

08:29.076 --> 08:30.942
       Oh, do you really
       think so, master?

08:30.944 --> 08:32.309
                        Yeah.

08:32.312 --> 08:33.979
            Do you have any idea
             what this could do

08:33.981 --> 08:35.647
              to the housewives
             all over the world?

08:35.649 --> 08:38.616
Well, they'll never have to wash
    clothes or mend anything.

08:38.619 --> 08:40.384
    Nothing will ever get dirty.
            Or torn.

08:40.385 --> 08:41.653
                 Or torn, right.
       Torn.

08:41.655 --> 08:43.621
         What are you doing?
     What are you doing to my--?

08:43.624 --> 08:44.956
    Well, what are you gonna do?

08:44.958 --> 08:47.191
  I want to cut a piece out
of this and have it analyzed.

08:47.193 --> 08:48.793
             What are you doing?

08:51.798 --> 08:53.498
I broke the scissors.

08:53.500 --> 08:54.532
                   The scissors.

08:54.534 --> 08:56.467
          I saw it.

08:56.469 --> 08:58.770
       Your blouse broke
         the scissors.

08:58.772 --> 09:00.371
        Well, how do you
      explain that, major?

09:00.373 --> 09:02.741
     Well, it's part of the same
    experiment we're working on.

09:02.743 --> 09:04.609
      Well, then why didn't
      the other fluid work?

09:04.611 --> 09:05.744
Oh, the other?

09:05.746 --> 09:07.345
    Well, it, uh,
probably wasn't fresh.

09:07.347 --> 09:09.347
         No, it has to be fresh.
Right. Exactly.

09:09.349 --> 09:10.715
           Is this fresh?

09:10.717 --> 09:12.784
                     Yes.
             Oh, we just got it.

09:12.786 --> 09:15.920
         If you don't mind,
          I'll take this.

09:20.360 --> 09:22.127
  Why don't he get
  his own coffee?

09:22.129 --> 09:23.394
                          Tea.
     Tea.

09:24.598 --> 09:27.365
           Believe me, general,
         I know what went wrong.

09:27.367 --> 09:30.468
      The X Factor wasn't fresh.

09:30.470 --> 09:32.470
The X Factor wasn't fresh.

09:32.472 --> 09:34.972
                I've just seen
              this demonstrated.

09:34.974 --> 09:36.974
       Watch the scissors break.

09:51.925 --> 09:54.092
     Did you realize we can make
        anything in the world

09:54.094 --> 09:55.259
             with this material?

09:55.261 --> 09:57.394
            We can make suits
        and dresses and fabrics.

09:57.396 --> 09:58.863
               There's no limit
              to what we can do.

09:58.865 --> 10:00.832
Roger, we're not gonna make
    anything out of it.

10:00.834 --> 10:02.834
       Oh, but why, master?
Well, think, Jeannie,

10:02.836 --> 10:04.135
if this ever got
 on the market,

10:04.137 --> 10:06.337
it could-- Well, it could
destroy our whole economy.

10:06.339 --> 10:08.906
 I don't think there'd be
a fabric firm in existence.

10:08.908 --> 10:09.907
It would affect, uh--

10:09.909 --> 10:11.709
Well, tailoring establishments,

10:11.711 --> 10:15.880
  and, uh, cleaning and--
And clothing manufacturers,

10:15.882 --> 10:17.982
and finally, it'd get
   down to trucks

10:17.984 --> 10:19.817
and railroad cars
  and gasoline.

10:19.819 --> 10:21.185
               You dirty blouse.

10:21.187 --> 10:23.187
             Let's destroy it
          before it destroys us.

10:23.189 --> 10:26.824
How are you going to destroy it?
I'm gonna burn it.

10:26.826 --> 10:29.326
    Here. But I do not think
     it will burn, master.

10:29.328 --> 10:31.829
I wasn't planning
on using a match.

10:31.831 --> 10:33.831
             [♪♪♪]

10:43.076 --> 10:44.909
      I'll hold the torch, Tony.
             You light it.

10:46.913 --> 10:48.479
                   There we are.

10:49.415 --> 10:52.283
                        Here.
                    You hold it.

10:52.285 --> 10:54.819
                     Let's get
                   this thing...

10:54.821 --> 10:57.555
                   There we are.

11:02.328 --> 11:03.461
    Stand back.

11:05.799 --> 11:07.097
        [DOORBELL RINGS]

11:07.099 --> 11:09.967
                 ROGER:
        Watch that we don't burn
            the garage down.

11:11.504 --> 11:12.904
      All right.
Let's give this a try.

11:16.709 --> 11:19.444
  There's not a mark on it.
             I can't believe it.

11:19.446 --> 11:20.611
I don't believe it, either.

11:20.613 --> 11:22.447
   But I--
I just saw it.

11:25.184 --> 11:27.151
     BELLOWS:
You shot that flame
  at this blouse.

11:27.153 --> 11:28.853
         TONY:
Yes, I-- I-- Yes, I did.

11:28.855 --> 11:30.321
     You saw it, Major Healey.

11:30.323 --> 11:31.689
                 Well, I...

11:31.691 --> 11:34.826
 And this blouse is untouched.
     You said so yourself.

11:34.828 --> 11:37.361
 Did I? Yeah.
Oh, I did. Yes.

11:37.363 --> 11:39.296
Don't think I don't know
what you're up to.

11:39.298 --> 11:41.733
     You're trying to keep
       this to yourself.

11:41.735 --> 11:44.368
         TONY:
      Oh, no, sir.
It's just not ready yet.

11:44.370 --> 11:47.872
          BELLOWS:
  I want the secret formula
that you used on this, major.

11:47.874 --> 11:49.540
          The X Factor.

11:49.542 --> 11:51.208
Uh, we just ran out, sir.

11:51.210 --> 11:53.711
   As a matter of fact,
we just ran out right now.

11:54.814 --> 11:56.113
               What's this?

12:00.153 --> 12:02.287
               "Secret Formula."

12:04.390 --> 12:06.291
                         Uh-huh.

12:06.293 --> 12:07.892
                     "X Factor."

12:07.894 --> 12:08.927
                     This is it.

12:08.929 --> 12:10.028
Oh, no, sir.

12:10.030 --> 12:11.429
That's really not it.
     It's not--

12:11.431 --> 12:13.832
                  I'll just take
                   this with me.

12:13.834 --> 12:15.633
[STAMMERING]
Sir, you see, it's not--

12:15.635 --> 12:17.302
It's still
in the experimental stage.

12:17.304 --> 12:19.871
    Mm, Major Nelson, I want you
     to keep yourself available.

12:19.873 --> 12:23.641
         Unless I miss my guess,
             within 24 hours,

12:23.643 --> 12:26.311
              we're going to be
             at the White House.

12:31.852 --> 12:33.918
      Now, keep your eye
    on the blouse, general.

12:33.920 --> 12:35.720
   It won't even be touched.

12:37.824 --> 12:39.824
             [♪♪♪]

12:51.304 --> 12:53.304
             [♪♪♪]

12:56.343 --> 12:57.842
  Here. Let me get it
        for you.

13:07.420 --> 13:09.854
    Are you moving
to another office, sir?

13:09.856 --> 13:13.024
             You might say that.
                 Permanently.

13:13.026 --> 13:14.425
I beg your pardon, sir?

13:14.427 --> 13:15.826
      Oh, haven't they told you?

13:15.828 --> 13:19.264
General Peterson has transferred
     me out of Cape Kennedy.

13:19.266 --> 13:20.464
          Why?

13:20.466 --> 13:22.267
            Because he's found
         a place where he thinks

13:22.269 --> 13:24.435
         I might be more useful.

13:24.437 --> 13:26.938
                      I'm going
                     to Iceland.
    Sir?

13:26.940 --> 13:29.707
        To work with the Eskimo.

13:29.709 --> 13:31.776
Why would General Peterson
  do a thing like that?

13:31.778 --> 13:33.744
           Your X Factor, major.

13:33.746 --> 13:35.113
     My what?

13:35.115 --> 13:37.115
            Well, I, uh...

13:37.117 --> 13:40.785
         I tried to show
 General Peterson how it worked.

13:40.787 --> 13:43.554
               I destroyed three
                of his uniforms.

13:43.556 --> 13:45.823
  You didn't.

13:45.825 --> 13:47.258
          I don't understand it,

13:47.260 --> 13:51.562
but, uh, the X Factor seems only
  to have worked for you, yes?

13:51.564 --> 13:53.631
   Sir, if I knew you were gonna
       do a thing like that,

13:53.633 --> 13:56.401
       I would have stopped you.

13:56.403 --> 13:57.668
 Would you?
                    Yes.

13:59.272 --> 14:01.939
     I'm sorry I couldn't have
  stayed around here long enough

14:01.941 --> 14:04.342
to find out what makes you tick.

14:04.344 --> 14:08.246
         Next to me, you're
   probably the most interesting

14:08.248 --> 14:10.348
          psychiatric case
       I've ever come across.

14:10.350 --> 14:11.515
         Next to you, sir?

14:11.517 --> 14:12.850
               Yes.

14:12.852 --> 14:15.053
        Sometimes I think
       I'm losing my mind.

14:15.055 --> 14:18.456
 One minute I'm rational
and then the next minute--

14:18.458 --> 14:21.459
         You do things that--

14:21.461 --> 14:25.429
   Oh, well, maybe the Eskimos
       will be good for me.

14:25.431 --> 14:26.730
       They're simple people.

14:28.667 --> 14:32.803
  They don't float in the air
 or change the days of the week

14:32.805 --> 14:34.372
     or control the weather.

14:34.374 --> 14:36.874
   Sir, perhaps if I have a word
  with General Peterson myself--

14:36.876 --> 14:39.510
   It won't do any good.
He's in a very upset state.

14:39.512 --> 14:42.579
I, uh-- When I left him,
   he was bellowing.

14:42.581 --> 14:43.580
   No, I--

14:44.784 --> 14:46.284
          I wouldn't go in there
              if I were you.

14:46.286 --> 14:47.418
Uh, sir, perhaps--

14:47.420 --> 14:49.486
 Oh, I'd appreciate it very much

14:49.488 --> 14:51.289
            if you'd write to me
              from time to time

14:51.291 --> 14:53.590
            and, uh, let me know
               what you're...

14:55.962 --> 14:58.395
                      doing.

14:58.397 --> 15:00.564
   Yes, sir.

15:00.566 --> 15:01.933
Good luck, sir.

15:01.935 --> 15:03.234
                  Thank you.

15:11.377 --> 15:12.376
           [WHISTLES]

15:12.378 --> 15:14.412
         Quartermaster?

15:14.414 --> 15:16.247
      Oh, hi, captain.

15:16.249 --> 15:18.349
 Yeah, this is Major Healey.
           Mm-hm.

15:18.351 --> 15:20.150
  Look, I was just wondering,

15:20.152 --> 15:23.254
      how much do we spend
      a year on uniforms?

15:23.256 --> 15:25.556
        Oh, that much.

15:25.558 --> 15:26.724
  Look, I was just wondering,

15:26.726 --> 15:29.427
    uh, what would you think
        about this, uh--

15:29.429 --> 15:31.929
       What if I came up
         with a uniform

15:31.931 --> 15:36.133
 that if you put grease on it,
       it wouldn't spot.

15:36.135 --> 15:37.335
        Uh-huh, uh-huh.

15:37.337 --> 15:38.736
    And you couldn't cut it.

15:38.738 --> 15:40.838
  I mean, you couldn't tear it
     or rip it or anything.

15:40.840 --> 15:43.107
 Or, if you put a torch to it,
       it wouldn't burn.

15:43.109 --> 15:45.476
         [LINE CLICKS]

15:45.478 --> 15:46.611
        Captain?

15:53.786 --> 15:55.552
Why would I keep
Dr. Bellows here?

15:55.554 --> 15:57.088
He's dangerous.

15:57.090 --> 15:58.789
          Well, sir, I've worked
             with Dr. Bellows

15:58.791 --> 15:59.990
         for the last two years.

15:59.992 --> 16:02.226
    And believe me, he's a man--
I know what he is.

16:02.228 --> 16:03.393
He walked into this office,

16:03.395 --> 16:05.096
  said we were going
 to Washington, D.C.,

16:05.098 --> 16:07.064
put some fly spray on me,
  and he smeared grease

16:07.066 --> 16:08.999
all over my uniform.

16:09.001 --> 16:10.101
                  Yes, but I-I--

16:10.103 --> 16:12.103
   Then he came back
with a pair of scissors,

16:12.105 --> 16:15.773
put some tea on me and started
 cutting up another uniform.

16:15.775 --> 16:18.976
  And then he came in,
and he set fire to this.

16:21.080 --> 16:22.747
        Kind of scorched it.

16:24.150 --> 16:27.852
    I-I-I don't suppose
    it could be patched.

16:27.854 --> 16:29.353
            I've got to get him
                out of here

16:29.355 --> 16:30.521
before I run out of clothes.

16:30.523 --> 16:32.122
Look what I gotta wear!

16:32.124 --> 16:34.692
  Well, uh, you see, Dr. Bellows
   is rather highly-strung, sir.

16:34.694 --> 16:36.961
 Highly-strung?
 He's snapped.

16:36.963 --> 16:39.129
      I'm sure if you'd give him
       another chance, general,

16:39.131 --> 16:40.998
               he would be--
If I gave him another chance,

16:41.000 --> 16:42.700
by next Monday
I'd be naked.

16:42.702 --> 16:43.900
             No, sir.

16:43.902 --> 16:46.470
      Let the Eskimos worry
      about him for a while.

16:46.472 --> 16:49.973
      Well, I feel partially
  responsible for this, general.

16:49.975 --> 16:52.709
        You see, Dr. Bellows saw
           Major Healey and I

16:52.711 --> 16:54.211
       conducting an experiment,

16:54.213 --> 16:57.148
  and he thought we were able to
 take an ordinary piece of cloth

16:57.150 --> 16:58.949
             and make it
     practically indestructible.

16:58.951 --> 17:01.485
    Tony, I admire loyalty
          in any man.

17:01.487 --> 17:03.053
               I'm only coming
            to his defense, sir,

17:03.055 --> 17:05.222
          because I don't want
       to see an injustice done.

17:05.223 --> 17:07.424
Tony, I want to give you
    a little advice.

17:07.425 --> 17:08.692
                     Yes, sir.

17:08.694 --> 17:10.094
     It's the same advice
         I'd give you

17:10.096 --> 17:12.063
   if you were my own son.

17:12.065 --> 17:13.063
                  Yes, sir.

17:13.065 --> 17:15.333
           Get out.

17:15.335 --> 17:17.335
             [♪♪♪]

17:30.950 --> 17:32.316
           Check.

17:33.253 --> 17:35.186
                     [SIGHS]

17:43.929 --> 17:45.429
                  [LAUGHS]

17:45.431 --> 17:47.198
                    Checkmate.

17:48.434 --> 17:49.967
Congratulations.

17:49.969 --> 17:53.737
          Oh, thank you, master.

17:53.739 --> 17:55.839
              Is anything wrong?

17:55.841 --> 17:58.442
    They're sending
Dr. Bellows to Iceland.

17:58.444 --> 18:01.045
                    Oh!

18:01.047 --> 18:02.513
   And this does not please you?

18:02.515 --> 18:03.947
No. It does not please me.

18:03.949 --> 18:05.649
       Oh, well, where would you
            like him to go?

18:05.651 --> 18:07.151
I wouldn't like him
  to go anywhere.

18:07.153 --> 18:08.886
Jeannie, Dr. Bellows
 is being punished

18:08.888 --> 18:11.222
     for something
that was not his fault.

18:11.224 --> 18:13.891
    And would you like
to know whose fault it is?

18:13.893 --> 18:18.262
      Hm, no, I do not think so.

18:18.264 --> 18:20.097
One little wish.

18:20.099 --> 18:22.733
You grant Roger Healey
   one little wish,

18:22.735 --> 18:24.801
and we lose Dr. Bellows.

18:24.803 --> 18:26.103
He's a very good man.

18:26.105 --> 18:27.604
This base can't afford
     to lose him.

18:27.606 --> 18:29.973
         Well, did you explain
       this to General Peterson?

18:29.975 --> 18:30.974
General Peterson.

18:30.976 --> 18:33.077
He just tossed me
out of his office.

18:33.079 --> 18:34.178
                He-- He toss--

18:34.180 --> 18:35.579
                 [GRUNTING]
Now, wait a minute!

18:35.581 --> 18:36.713
 Now, don't, please.

18:36.715 --> 18:38.482
Not General Peterson.
 I don't need that.

18:38.484 --> 18:39.850
 No, I really don't need that.

18:39.852 --> 18:42.353
    Well, surely there must be
 someone above General Peterson?

18:42.355 --> 18:44.155
     Yeah. Well,
there's General Burke.

18:44.157 --> 18:46.623
That's his immediate superior.
  But he's at the Pentagon.

18:46.625 --> 18:48.459
   How would I ever
 explain that to him?

18:48.461 --> 18:50.827
       Oh, do not worry, master.
           I will explain it.

18:50.829 --> 18:52.229
       Yeah...

18:55.535 --> 18:57.535
             [♪♪♪]

19:01.240 --> 19:02.373
         Oh!

19:06.446 --> 19:08.379
   [JEANNIE'S VOICE]
Good afternoon, airman.

19:22.762 --> 19:24.027
      Yes?

19:24.029 --> 19:25.496
     Ah, it's General Patterson.

19:25.498 --> 19:26.564
    Peterson.

19:26.566 --> 19:28.132
               Ah, of course.

19:28.134 --> 19:29.433
            I'm Colonel Harris.

19:29.435 --> 19:30.735
          General Burke sent me.

19:30.737 --> 19:32.836
Well, I'm very happy
to know you, colonel.

19:32.838 --> 19:34.171
General Burke here?

19:34.173 --> 19:36.474
                  Here?
        No, he'll be down later.

19:36.476 --> 19:38.409
He wanted me to tell you
   how pleased he is

19:38.411 --> 19:40.210
with the work you've
been doing, general.

19:40.212 --> 19:41.579
                    Is he?

19:41.581 --> 19:43.847
                Well, we all try
                 to do our best.

19:43.849 --> 19:45.750
We have a good team here,
        you know.

19:45.752 --> 19:48.919
         Those are the general's
               exact words.

19:48.921 --> 19:51.021
           Um, may I tell you
        something in confidence?

19:51.023 --> 19:52.657
Why, certainly, colonel.

19:52.659 --> 19:54.858
          The reason the general
              is coming here

19:54.860 --> 19:56.894
                is to give
          a special commendation

19:56.896 --> 19:59.229
           to one of the members
               of your team.

19:59.231 --> 20:01.199
Well, that's wonderful.
      Who is he?

20:01.201 --> 20:02.866
            Uh, Dr. Bellows.

20:03.836 --> 20:05.302
           Dr. Bellows.

20:05.304 --> 20:08.839
       Uh, General Burke says
    he's been doing a great job.

20:08.841 --> 20:10.006
    Well, where is he, general?

20:10.008 --> 20:11.241
   Well, as a matter of fact,

20:11.243 --> 20:13.944
    Dr. Bellows is-- Is just
   leaving on a little trip.

20:13.946 --> 20:15.746
  He may even be gone by now.

20:15.748 --> 20:17.715
     General Burke is gonna be
         surprised to hear

20:17.717 --> 20:18.883
        you could spare him.

20:18.885 --> 20:20.585
          But I suppose
    it's just for the weekend.

20:20.587 --> 20:22.285
         You know, General Burke
             and Dr. Bellows

20:22.287 --> 20:23.921
             are old classmates.

20:23.923 --> 20:25.656
          Old classmates.

20:25.658 --> 20:26.757
        I didn't know that.

20:26.759 --> 20:28.192
               Oh, yes.

20:28.194 --> 20:30.194
         General Burke thinks
      the world of Dr. Bellows.

20:30.196 --> 20:31.662
             He does?

20:31.664 --> 20:33.730
       Yes, they're cousins.

20:33.732 --> 20:35.166
         They're cousins.

20:35.168 --> 20:37.568
            First cousins.

20:37.570 --> 20:40.304
       Well, I don't think
           Dr. Bellows

20:40.306 --> 20:42.506
      will be going away on
       that trip after all.

20:42.508 --> 20:44.408
      You tell General Burke
         I'd find it hard

20:44.410 --> 20:45.709
    to get along without him.

20:45.711 --> 20:47.344
             Oh, goody!

20:47.346 --> 20:49.880
      Um, uh, the General
 will be pleased to hear that.

20:49.882 --> 20:52.349
  Will you excuse me
for a moment, colonel?

20:52.351 --> 20:53.717
Just make yourself at home.

21:01.761 --> 21:03.093
            [LAUGHING]

21:04.697 --> 21:06.630
                  Whee!

21:24.349 --> 21:26.316
            Oh, Dr. Bellows, I--

21:26.318 --> 21:27.618
    Yes, general?

21:30.022 --> 21:31.388
  What are you doing?

21:31.390 --> 21:34.191
                       Doing?
                    I'm packing.

21:34.193 --> 21:37.027
         Packing?
     Where you going?

21:37.029 --> 21:38.028
               Where am I going?

21:38.030 --> 21:39.529
     You've sent me to Siberia--

21:39.531 --> 21:41.131
            Um, I mean, Iceland.

21:41.133 --> 21:43.533
Do you know the trouble
   with you, doctor?

21:43.535 --> 21:45.102
          [CHUCKLING]
     You're too sensitive.

21:45.104 --> 21:46.604
              I'm too sensitive?

21:46.606 --> 21:49.106
  Well, you don't really think
 we could get along around here

21:49.108 --> 21:50.540
            without you, did ya?

21:50.542 --> 21:54.478
 But, general, you ordered me
to pack my things and get out.

21:54.480 --> 21:56.179
                   [CHUCKLING]
                       Oh.

21:56.181 --> 21:57.781
     And you thought I meant it?

21:57.783 --> 21:59.182
Didn't you?

21:59.184 --> 22:01.852
    Well, as I was just saying
  to a friend of your cousin's,

22:01.854 --> 22:04.855
       I couldn't possibly
      get along without you.

22:04.857 --> 22:06.190
          My cousin's?

22:06.192 --> 22:09.760
          After all, uh,
      what's a few uniforms?

22:09.762 --> 22:15.633
   General, you mean I don't
  have to leave Cape Kennedy?

22:15.635 --> 22:18.368
           Why, I wouldn't dream
             of letting ya go.

22:18.370 --> 22:21.438
        I'll deduct the uniforms
             from your pay.

22:21.440 --> 22:23.140
I don't know what to say.

22:23.142 --> 22:24.808
       Well, don't say anything.

22:24.810 --> 22:27.111
                     And Doctor?
          Yes?

22:27.113 --> 22:29.813
      Try to get plenty of rest.

22:29.815 --> 22:31.548
  I certainly will.

22:31.550 --> 22:34.718
Oh, and I'm awfully sorry
  about your uniforms.

22:34.720 --> 22:35.819
                  Oh, forget it.

22:35.821 --> 22:37.888
Oh, I'll never forget it,
        general.

22:52.037 --> 22:53.403
        [BOTH LAUGHING]

22:53.405 --> 22:55.905
So Jeannie came back here,
and she called General Peterson

22:55.907 --> 22:58.308
and told him that General Burke
would not be able to make it

22:58.310 --> 22:59.776
until the later part
   of the month.

22:59.778 --> 23:01.044
           Oh, that's marvelous.

23:01.046 --> 23:02.912
     Well, I guess the old quack
          is still with us.

23:02.914 --> 23:05.115
He's not a quack, Roger.
He's a very competent man.

23:05.117 --> 23:06.883
     Oh, I enjoyed getting him
          out of trouble.

23:06.885 --> 23:07.884
       Mm.
Well, you should.

23:07.886 --> 23:09.586
You enjoyed getting him
into it enough.

23:09.588 --> 23:10.587
              I did not.

23:10.589 --> 23:11.955
You did too.
           Are you finished?

23:11.957 --> 23:13.323
 Huh? Yeah.

23:13.325 --> 23:14.525
Look, Jeannie--
             I did not.

23:14.527 --> 23:15.592
You did too.

23:15.594 --> 23:17.093
Listen, I know you
didn't mean to--

23:17.095 --> 23:19.129
        [ARGUING]

23:19.131 --> 23:20.964
         Wait a minute, will ya?

23:20.966 --> 23:22.866
    I'm the one that got cheated
          out of the wish.

23:22.868 --> 23:24.934
         I didn't get to finish
        my strawberry shortcake.

23:24.936 --> 23:27.103
    Now, all I want is one wish.
       What's wrong with that?

23:27.105 --> 23:28.272
No, no, Roger.
                      Just one.

23:28.274 --> 23:30.140
I'm not gonna grant...
             Now, wait a minute.

23:30.142 --> 23:31.441
Please, master, may I, please?

23:31.443 --> 23:33.544
Now, don't you start on me.
          She wants to give me--

23:33.546 --> 23:35.879
I've had enough
 of this. No!

23:35.881 --> 23:37.214
No-- All right!
  All right!

23:37.216 --> 23:38.415
                   All right?

23:38.417 --> 23:40.084
           You mean you're gonna
             give me one wish?

23:40.086 --> 23:41.585
            Oh, boy!
           I'm rich.

23:41.587 --> 23:42.786
  Oh, yachts and chateaus.

23:42.788 --> 23:44.454
      Chateaus and yachts.
                 Yeah, I got it.

23:44.456 --> 23:45.789
                   Wait, no.
               Wait, wait, wait!

23:45.791 --> 23:47.290
      I'll be a rich movie star,
              that's it.

23:47.292 --> 23:48.458
                   A movie star.
           Movie star?

23:48.460 --> 23:49.860
        Rich movie star.
                 No, no, no, no!

23:49.862 --> 23:51.729
     Oh, wait. Maybe I should be
           a brain surgeon.

23:51.731 --> 23:53.130
        Brain surgeon.

23:53.132 --> 23:55.665
Roger, you know, you're
the funniest man I've ever met.

23:55.667 --> 23:56.834
             You know something?

23:56.836 --> 23:58.736
         You know what I wished
        when I was a little boy?

23:58.738 --> 24:00.738
       I-I wished I were
 the funniest man in the world.

24:02.842 --> 24:05.442
             Here, you hold this
             and I'll hold this.

24:05.444 --> 24:06.509
                 Aw.

24:06.511 --> 24:08.178
          Hi, Groucho.

24:16.688 --> 24:18.688
             [♪♪♪]
